The Stomachion is an ancient puzzle that is at least 2,200 years old. It consists of 14 pieces that can be cut from a 12x12 square, as shown in the images. Like tangrams, the object of the Stomachion is to rearrange the pieces to form interesting shapes.

The pieces are 1 cm thick. Next time, I will probably reduce the thickness to 0.5 cm to save on PLA.

I was inspired by an article found on the NCTM website:
https://illuminations.nctm.org/Lesson.aspx?id=2523

I then used Tinkercad to design the puzzle pieces.

As a HS Geometry teacher, I feel there are many opportunities for investigation with this puzzle, from coordinate geometry, using an app like Geogebra to recreate the puzzle with polygons, bisectors and more, exploring congruent and similar figures, and analyzing surface area and volumes.

In addition, the students will be able to explore their creativity by creating their own designs with the pieces.

comments.text:
Hey Ben, welcome to the 3d printing world, I am really glad you are diving right in and remixing and designing.
A couple things that may effect how snug or loose a print in place design comes out:
Calibration is the first thing to think about. There are super simple instructions here. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:53668http://www.thingiverse.com/thi...
The other big differentiator is the nozzle size. I think most printers come with a .4, but you can get .5 and .35 from printrbot. You just unscrew the old one and pop the new one on. .35 will get you finer prints but it takes longer to get the material out.
Hope that helps!
PS. Right now I am designing a tolerance calculator so you can find out exactly what tolerances your printer can handle. Follow me if you'd like to be notified when I upload it.

title: Replacement for Java Presse plastic insert for burr

description.text:
This replaces the insert for the ceramic burr in your Java Presse coffee grinder. The original piece on ours cracked and stripped out the notches that the metal shaft grabs to spin the ceramic burr.

The original is nylon. I highly recommend printing it with nylon. I used Taulman 3D Nylon Alloy 910. Alloy 910 is an FDA approved material for direct food contact.

This version of the part fits the metal shaft a little tight. The advantage of it being tight is that it is less likely to strip out the notches than if it is loose. The disadvantage is that it wont slide freely on the shaft, so you have to give the burr a little help when you loosen the adjustment knob by pushing the shaft with your finger. I provided a step file, in case anyone wants to adjust dimensions to get a looser fit.

All you have to do to print Nylon on PEI is put a light layer of PVA (Elmer's purple glue stick is what i use) down on the bed and heat to 60C. The film of PVA will wash off the bed and the part with water.

Be sure to wash the part with water before use. Nylon Alloy 910 is approved for direct food contact. But, if you used Elmers glue for bed adhesion, you will want to get it off the bottom of the part before grinding coffee. Elmer's glue is non-toxic, but I still don't want it in my coffee.

title: Cheeky Santa Earrings, Tree & Cake Decoration

description.text:
This started as a request from my good lady for some novelty earrings to be ready for Christmas! Now there's a Mrs Santa!!! See the Mk2 version link at the bottom
Not wanting to start from scratch I've remixed an existing Santa file, see below for the original. The design may not be to everyone's taste but if not then just smile and move on.
The file was loaded into Meshmixer and the alterations begun. The clothing was shrunk to form the body, the hat was shrunk to form the hanger. The beard and face reworked slightly and obviously a new hat created to hide his necessaries. The hats bobble was attached to his leg to remove the need for support. His forearms and hand were adjusted to hold the hat and with a little bit of body sculpting he was ready for setting up for printing. All the printing has been with pink (manufacturer refers to it as Skin) PLA.
The Earrings. The file was loaded into Cura and his height adjusted to 40mm with a layer height of 0.2mm and 0% fill. A brim was added to keep him stable during printing. A left hand and right hand version can be made as in the photos by flipping the X axis in Cura. Once printed the hanger hole will need cleaning out carefully with a 1mm drill bit and when the brim has been cleaned off he is ready for a fine paint brush and a steady hand. When dry the earring hooks can be added and they are ready for use.
The Christmas tree decoration. Again the file was loaded into Cura and the height adjusted to 80mm or whatever you think is suitable. A layer height was set at 0.2mm with 0% fill. An 80mm print needed the hanger cleaning out with a 2mm drill bit. Once again the brim need cleaning off then he needs painting and he's ready for the tree.
Cake topper/decoration. ... and then someone said if he didn't have a hanger on the top of his head you could use him for a Christmas cake decoration, a cake topper! So back into Meshmixer, hanger removed, into Cura with the same settings. Z height set to 75mm, layer height 0.2mm with 0% fill with brim for stability when printing. The brim removed and a quick paint job and there you have him. The brim or a raft could be added and left on to aid mounting on the cake but I'll let you tinker with that one.

description.text:
A redo of my Filament box with monitoring and auto pause if filament jams or breaks. That's the idea anyway. Getting the top off with the filament coming through it was like fighting an octopus. So MK2 it comes out the side through 4x2 Teflon tubing, passes through the counters and up to the printer.

The monitor has 4 states;
1: Just sitting doing nothing, all LED's on
2: Waiting for regular movement, Blue LED. About 15 seconds of movement. either feed.
3: Monitoring, Green LED. As long as it does not stop for 15 seconds, either feed.
4: Paused, RED LED and Pause connection held low. Also beeps.

Still a work in progress, the electronics will be stripboarded and boxed. Still need to connect it to the printer Pause connection. I think it can be powered from there also. some research needed. Using the old box.
The box lid needs some material removal so the clip clears the monitors to get the lid off.
Probably going to fit the push-fit connectors on the top outlet of the monitor.

Been working on the ESP8266 Micropython code, I was running into lack of RAM problems but after a good deal of googling I can now roll my own firmware with the code built in, saves a shed load of ram. I will post a .bin file when it is in a finished state. Just a case of flashing it to a suitable ESP8266 board at that point. Also changed the 3 led's to a single NeoPixel.
Added box parts for circuit boards. Also Fritzing circuit file and MicroPython ESP8266 firmware file for flashing. Python files that are baked into firmware.

Swapped back to Arduino code on the ESP8266 as the MicroPython code was unreliable.

Arduino files

I have added two arduino files for uploading onto a ESP8266. I am using a WeMos D1 mini but any of the development boards should work.

One file has just a local web page to display the job status.
The other has the same Web page but on port 81, and will also update a ThingSpeak channel with 6 fields.

machine status 0: stopped, 1: waiting, 2: running, 3:paused
filament 1 status 0:Stopped, 1:Moving

You could have it send you a text or a tweet on pause.

description.text:
This is a simple test I ran on my Form 2 printer to see if it was possible to print a micro/millifluidic system. I wanted to try out several geometries to see if a) they could be printed and b) if they offered any advantage. I'm particularly interested in a channel with a twisted 3 dimensional structure, that simulates natural capillaries, is beneficial when moving cells around the system.
I'm happy to state that at least the first stage worked and all channels could be printed, cleaned out, and allow liquid to flow through them. Cell studies will have to wait until later.

Notes:

This was printed on a Form 2 but this isn't an option so I selected form 1.

Cleaning and coating.

I used the Formlabs supplied bottle to squeeze IPA down the channels. This was fiddly to do and if you have a syringe I suggest you use that. I left to dry and then, after ensuring the channels were clear, I cured it in the UV cabinet.

I sanded down the sides to 2000 grit, although that probably wasn't worth it. I then applied an acrylic spray clear coating which allowed easy view of the internal channels.

Design

I used Blender to design the part. I created a bezier curve helix and then used the simple deform and curve modifiers to create the channels.

title: TRON Arcade Cabinet PC Board Supports

description.text:
Been restoring (more like rebuilding) a 1982 TRON upright arcade game and there were various bits missing. These are a set of supports for the logic board stack. There are slots in the surface of the supports for the PC board to seat into.

These raise the boards a good deal more off of the cabinet bottom than the original factory supports, in part to avoid the possibility of damage to the boards if the cabinet leveling legs were screwed down too far.

While designed for the upright cabinet, these could likely be used in the cabaret or cocktail cabinets as well.

Printer:

XYZ Printing DaVinci 2.0

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

100%

Notes:

The solid infill might be a little overkill, but I was going for rigidity since the board stack does have a bit of weight to it.

The cross bracing on the lower bracket does not extend all the way to the bottom in order to allow for cleaning without removing the bracket/board stack.

The securing tabs on the upper bracket are slotted to east installation/removal of the logic board stack by loosening the securing screws.

title: Monoprice MP Select Mini Filament Guide

description.text:
This is a quick design that prevents kinks in filament as it's pulled by the extruder. It attaches via the sheet metal screw on the top of the printer's z axis tower.

I printed it at 3 shells 20% infill- just enough to make sure that the part underneath the screw is solid. Let me know if you have any problems!

One more tip: it really helps if you can get the support to go at a 45 degree angle "into" the groove. This is really important to adequately support the print above. The gcode I posted does this.

Update: mine squeaks a little as the filament rubs against it. I haven't had the time to try sanding it down yet though. Let me know if you have the same issue!

Update: the squeaking goes away after the area is worn smooth!

Printer:

Monoprice MP Select Mini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.25

Infill:

20%

Notes:

The gcode included is for the MP Select Mini- PLA at 195/50. After it prints, remove supports. Unscrew the screw at the top of the printer, being careful not to lose the washer. Place the guide over the hole and screw the sheet metal screw back in the same place. Tighten firmly, but slowly, so as not to cause too much stress on the material.

comments.text: Hello! Resolution is the thickness of the layers. 0.25mm is a medium-low resolution. The layers are thicker, so the part prints faster at the cost of surface quality and detail. Since this is a simple part though, 0.25 is fine. Larger numbers are considered lower resolutions; smaller numbers are higher resolutions. Standard is about 0.2mm (though that is subject to personal preference).

title: SelectVu - Noire style Reprap Smart Controller housing

description.text:
NOTE: A VERSION FOR SMALLER BEDS IS STILL IN THE WORKS. Print services available - message me.

This is a housing I made for a RepRapDiscount Smart Controller (2004 style) that i added to my Printrbot Simple Metal. I will be making an 'outboard' style stand as an option to accommodate other printer models. Message me if you need a custom stand or mount.

The LCD frame and the buzzer ring bezel were both printed with aluminum-pla filament. These optional details will be available so you can do your own color scheme. The reset button is not completed yet. For now, there is just a 1.75mm red filament but a screw or other secure scheme with a button cap will be added to this design.

Note: The Printrbot firmware I am using does not utilize the SD slot, the beeper or the system halt button (wah!) but this design does allow access to those features so you have the option of using with your own firmware mod (or another model printer). I am working on making these active so I decided not to cover these components up.

Printer Brand:

Printrbot

Printer:

Simple Black

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

This was printed on a Printrbot Simple Metal with the 10" x-axis upgrade. I will set up a version for smaller print beds if requests come in for it.

For the Printrbot stand, 2 are required. it was designed to mount with M3 screws and nuts.

The current version of this design works but will be fine-tuned to allow for use with M3 screws. I was able to fasten it together without nuts (the screws will self-tap). If you wish to add LCD and buzzer fitments they can be attached with craft glue or double-face 3M.

The texture vinyl was trimmed using a stencil of the face plate and most of the rough edges are hidden by the fitments. I was too lazy to drag out my vinyl cutter to make a better fit (space limitations at the lab lately).

This was designed from scratch in DesignSpark Mechanical. I took measurements with calipers to get the main outer dimensions, and approximate placement of the screw holes, beeper, reset button, and LCD. I did a quick outline sketch of the faceplate and mockup with the cutout holes and pulled the plate thickness to a few mils so I could test and refine all hole locations. The outer length and width were adjusted to allow for a housing wall to be incorporated as part of the face plate. I had also measured and placed the pegs for the LCD board.

After a few test prints and placement adjustments of the pegs, screw standoffs and other details, I re-checked and adjusted the design to allow any gap needed between the circuit board edges and the wall. A back-plate was added to make this a fully enclosed assembly.

description.text:
Decided to make those cargo cover holders useful in my Runner. Wanted to add a fire extinguisher for some extra peace of mind...just in case...and thought these pockets may work well. There are 4 parts to this model. (1) The adapter plate: This inserts into the place where the original holder was at. It is partially recessed in the pocket (for extra stability) and uses the 2 factory screws for attachment. It also has pockets in the back for (4) 1/4 28 nuts. (2) Mount plate: This plate mounts to the adapter plate. It is set up for 1/4 28 x 1" flat-head screws. It mounts to (and over, for extra strength) the adapter plate, then gets screwed in place. It has a dovetail in which the FE holder will mount. (3) The fire extinguisher (FE) holder: It has a corresponding dovetail which slides into the mount plate and a top plate to stop it in place. There are also some notches for 2 hose clamps to secure the FE. (4) Pin: this little pin goes through both the mount plate and holder to keep everything secure.

To use...pull the pin and slide the holder with fire extinguisher up and out of the mount plate...

The fire extinguisher is a Harbor Freight buy...the 2lb one...#62634

I also added a blank adapter plate if someone wants to make some other device using this pocket space. Also, this was made specifically for a 97 Runner...there was a change to some interior components halfway through this gen so it may or may not fit those later years. This is set up for the driver's side pocket. You'd have to mirror image the adapter plate model if you wanted it on the passenger's side. Enjoy...!

title: Prusa I3 Pro B "Pertinax" frame top bar strengthening brackets

description.text:
Since I replaced the Z axis spindles of my cheap Chinese i3 clone against better trapezoid threaded rods, I have two spare wobbly M8 rods which were intended to go into the frame, with the purpose of strengthening it. As the top horizontal bar of those printers is candidate to attaching all kinds of stuff to it, like reels with filament, tools, displays, filament guides etc, the resulting load put on this skimpy part of the frame may become considerable, and may need support. One of those spare M8 rods will do nicely for this purpose, thereby also increasing resistance against torsive forces, in addition to support along gravitational vector.
Here are the rather simplistic brackets which go with it. The presets fit my "Zhuhai Prusa i3 Pro B" with layered 5.5mm Pertinax-like frame nicely. They attach to the frame just behind the Z top brackets, holding the M8 rod which is oriented along X axis, slightly elevated to provide space for mounting things on it.

9/4/17 EDIT
I revamped the pommel to match the movie version exactly; there is also an added hole to insert a D-Ring. I also added a new panel that can be glued into the side of the ignition switch, adding more authenticity to the overall prop. This is a collection of hex bases designed to fit over the raised center sections of Heroscape tiles, in several sizes and shapes. There are nine designs -- one- to five-hex linear rows, a three-hex triangle, a four-hex diamond, a two-by-three-hex block, and a seven-hex circle. These can be used to create terrain objects by attaching objects to the face of the base, which can then be placed on a mapboard.

The bases are printed inverted to remove any bridging issues.

The single base is sized to fit over a 38mm face-to-face raised hex; all the other bases are sized to fit over 38mm hexes separated by 44.5mm, matching the hex pattern of Heroscape tiles.

The source file in OpenSCAD generates correctly-sized bases with a unit measurement in OpenSCAD being 0.1mm when I load the resulting STL file into the front-end software for my 3D printer; if your slicing software correctly takes 1 unit as 1mm, then scale down the STL file by a factor of 10 to produce the correct size.

comments.author: JenniferG

comments.text: When I do the design in OpenSCAD, the STL files scale in the frontend software I load STL files into to slice and send to my 3D printer -- a Flux Delta -- at the correct size; I'm not sure why the OpenSCAD units work out at 10 units per millimeter, but it's a convenient number; if you're seeing them as grossly oversized, scaling them to 1/10 their size should produce the correct dimensions -- the one-hex base should be a little under 50mm corner-to-corner (I don't have the precise measurement on me; I'm at work).

title: Tevo Black Widow 15 Degree Extruder Mount

description.text:
This extruder mounting bracket for the Tevo Black Widow will give you additional X-axis and Z-axis travel by angling the extruder motor away from the right-side Z carriage plate, moving the print head closer to the center of the X carriage, and by raising the extruder/hot end assembly by 18mm.

I have provided the mounting bracket in one-piece and two-piece options. You can decide whether to print the one-piece and deal with the extra supports to remove or using an extra low profile M5 screw and M5 nut to put the two-piece together. It may also be a good idea to glue the two-piece version together to improve rigidity.

I have also provided files for mounting the X-axis end stop at the very end of the X-axis extrusion. Choose either right or left depending on where you have your sensor located.

You will need this additional hardware to mount the bracket to the X carriage plate:

2 x M5 nylon insert lock nut
2 x M5x12mm screws (M5 x 10mm might work)

In addition, for the two piece you will need these to hold the two pieces together:

1 x Low Profile M5x10mm screw
1 x Standard M5 nut
Thread locker (optional)

For mounting the end stop sensor to the new end stop mount, in addition to the M4 screw and T-nut from the stock mount you will need:

1 x M3x10mm screw
1 x M3 nut
